    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.\n\nWe currently decide on a general basis which utility code we extract into the shared module and which not, thus making the shared module larger or the user modules larger for everyone. Some features are large, some are just widely used, some are large and less widely used, which leaves us with a permanent trade-off.\n\nIf users could easily select certain features in or out, then they could adapt the shared module to their needs and take the trade-off decision themselves.\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like.\n\nI envision a positive list of general features that users want to see included, configured as part of the shared module setup.\nThis list would then be mapped to a larger list of utility code names that Cython uses internally.\n\nThe list wouldn't have to be exhaustive but only list major features like\n- `memoryview`\n- `import`\n- `pickle`\n- `extensiontypes`\n- `fusedfunction`\n- `builtins` (possible more specific, like `builtinstr`)\n\nTo allow adding to this list later, Cython should just ignore (and probably warn about) unknown feature names that future Cython version might understand. Something that's unknown now would not end up in the shared module anyway (or users must depend on a later Cython version).\n\nIt's probably fine to constrain this configuration to the shared module, at least for the beginning. If users want to use features in their code that they excluded from the shared module, then they'll get a failure at import time at the latest, which seems fine.\nAlternatively, we could be nice and automatically put excluded shared code into the user module if that's easily possible, but that doesn't seem a required feature.\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered.\n\nWe could provide include/exclude configuration options. I think that a single positive list has the advantage of allowing future feature additions that would automatically be excluded by existing builds that don't use them anyway. OTOH, if we decide to add a complete _existing_ feature to the list of shared code, users of this feature would have to adapt their setup in order to use a new Cython version. That seems fine, given the \"ignore unknown names\" constraint and the presumably low frequency of this happening.\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
